A passport office had to be evacuated after a suspicious package containing a white powder was sent to the building. Emergency services were called to the Passport Office in Newport, Wales shortly after 8.35am following reports of a suspicious package. As a result, the building was evacuated and remained sealed off for more than two hours while the item, and white powder inside, was examined. Photos from the scene showed a large number of emergency service response vehicles outside the building. Shortly after 11.30am Gwent police confirmed the powder was not toxic or harmful to touch and the office was reopened. A spokesperson for Gwent Police said: ‘We received a call at about 8.40am this morning regarding concerns about a suspicious package received at the Passport Office in Newport. ‘The fire service has attended and have evacuated the building as a precaution whilst they carry out further enquiries.’ In an update the force said: ‘The fire service examined the suspicious package that contained white powder and it was found not be toxic or harmful to touch, therefore the passport has been reopened.’ In a statement, South Wales Fire Service confirmed crews were called to the office shortly after 8.35am. ‘Crews from Whitchurch and Maindee Fire and Rescue Stations are currently in attendance alongside emergency service colleagues,’ the service said. ‘Crews have evacuated the building as a safety precaution whilst teams carry out further investigations.’ Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page.